AB  - During and immediately after World War II, immigration reform advocacy groups successfully challenged the restrictionist spirit of the 1924 Immigration Act by blocking several proposals to halt immigration and by pushing for moderate reforms. Concerned that the blatantly racist act undermined US foreign policy interests and tarnished the country's image abroad, Congress, with the full support of the executive, repealed Chinese exclusion laws; granted citizenship and naturalization rights to Indians and Filipinos; and admitted war brides, fiancées, and European refugees outside the quota system. Marinari argues the debate and the negotiations over the 1952 Immigration and Nationality Act demonstrate the limits of the inclusiveness of the US political system during the early years of the Cold War and the difficulties of creating diverse coalitions among ethnically diverse immigration reform advocates.
