AB  - Using data from the National Latino and Asian American Study (NLAAS), this study explores psychological distress in Latino/Latino intraracial and Latino/White interracial relationships. The term Latino refers to ethnicity, which emphasizes national origin as opposed to race. However, this paper classifies Latino relationships as either an intraracial or interracial relationship for the sake of consistency and simplicity. A social stress framework informs this study as two stressors-perceived discrimination and relationship satisfaction-are examined in relationship to distress. The buffering effect of social support is observed as well. Results show that perceived discrimination is an important stressor for both relationship groups, but relationship satisfaction is only important for Latino/Latino relationships. Social support buffers the impact of discrimination, but only for Latino/Latino relationships. Interaction effects that explore the influence of gender and social class with key explanatory variables are also investigated.
